            },
            {
               "text": "### Prerequisites\n\nThis text will expand your understanding of division (sharing) studied in the previous lessons. Therefore, we recommend reviewing all the previous texts from Chapter 6 in the *First Steps* section of **History Tracers** (<htcite0>) before continuing.",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 3210,
                     "uuid": "b5efc8f9-c268-430f-9681-7a43848ee48e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "First Steps",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nWhen we study multiplication tables, we learn that they show the results of repeated addition (<htcite0>). As a result, they do not show the values between the multiplication results.\n\nLet’s recall the 4 times table:",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "eaa59295-fb80-4c33-b1e4-bcdf3c11dabf",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Sumando los mismos números",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2025",
                        "month": "-1",
                        "day": "-1"
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div id=\"mParent4\" style=\"margin: auto; text-align: center;\"></div></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "In this table, the numbers increase by 4 each time, and as a result, the number 5 does not appear.\n\nThis is also related to division, which we are currently studying — a fact that leads us to reflect:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: There’s some left over...</b><br /><br />If we have 8 apples and want to share them with one other person, each person will get 4 (8/8 = 4/8 + 4/8).<br /><br />Now, what if we have 5 apples and want to share them among 4 people?<br /><br />How would you do it?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_visual",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Visualizing the Remainder\n\nLet’s once again use a sheet of paper to visualize what we are studying.\n\n#### Practice",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_lab_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_lab question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-microscope\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_lab\"><b>Practice 1</b><br /><br />1. Take a sheet of paper and divide it as shown in <b>Table 1</b>, so that it has 4 rectangles.<br />2. Take 5 small objects, each smaller than the rectangles, and place one object in each rectangle. In <b>Table 1</b>, this is illustrated with a rectangle that could represent another cut-out piece of paper.</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"sequenceNum\" class=\"tableTen\"><tr><th colspan=\"2\">Sheet divided inta 4o</th></tr><tr><td style=\"height: 100px; background-color: lightblue; text-aligh: center;\"><spam class=\"text_to_paint\">|</spam></td><td style=\"height: 100px; background-color: lightblue; text-aligh: center;\"><spam class=\"text_to_paint\">|</spam></td></tr><tr><td style=\"height: 100px; background-color: lightblue; text-aligh: center;\"><spam class=\"text_to_paint\">|</spam></td><td style=\"height: 100px; background-color: lightblue; text-aligh: center;\"><spam class=\"text_to_paint\">|</spam></td></tr> </table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 1</b>: Representation of a blank sheet divided into four parts, each containing one rectangle.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "Since we have 5 objects, this means that one is left over. This remainder is shown in **Table 2**:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><table id=\"sequenceNum\" class=\"tableTen\" style=\"width: 200px;\"><tr><th>Remaining rectangle</th></tr><tr><td style=\"height: 100px; width: 100px; text-aligh: center; border: none;\"><spam class=\"text_to_paint\">|</spam></td></tr> </table></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Table 2</b>: Representation of one remaining rectangle</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "#### Beyond the Whole\n\nWhen we write this practice as a fraction, we get the following result:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mfrac><mrow> <mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mrow> </mfrac></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 1</b>: Representation of the practice in fraction form.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "When the numerator (the top part of the fraction) is greater than the denominator (the bottom part), it means there are more objects (numerator) than parts available to distribute (denominator).\n\nAlthough this concept is slightly different from what we have studied before, it does not change the meaning of the denominator, which still represents the whole.\n\nTherefore, we should interpret that the number of rectangles we have is greater than the total that makes up one whole.\n\nOn the other hand, if there were only 4 rectangles, we would have a distribution that represents exactly the whole, as shown in **Calculation 2**:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><math mathsize=\"1.5em\"> <mn>1</mn> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac><mrow> <mn>4</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mrow> </mfrac></p><p class=\"desc\"><b>Calculation 2</b>: Representation of the practice in fraction form showing a complete whole.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
   ],
   "exercise_v2": [
      {
         "question": "É possível o numerador ser maior que o denominador?",
         "yesNoAnswer": "Yes",
         "additionalInfo": "Quando temos mais valores para distribuir que o total disponível, como vimos neste texto, o numerador terá um valor maior que o denominador."
      }
   ],
